text: Yes, a blocked alveoli can cause a V/Q mismatch. When an alveolus is blocked, it can lead to a decrease in ventilation (V) and an increase in perfusion (Q) in the affected area. This results in an unequal distribution of ventilation and perfusion, which is referred to as a V/Q mismatch. This can be seen on imaging studies like a chest X-ray, where areas of increased perfusion may appear more opaque or "whiter" compared to the surrounding lung tissue.
